</style>EGI.eu has contributed to a new European Commission report on Service Level Agreements in the cloud computing arena.</p></div>
<!--  end optional summary div  -->


 <p>In recent years cloud computing has become a popular way of exploiting IT resources. This has led to many national and European projects using cloud platforms, and others, like <a href="/infrastructure/cloud/">EGI&rsquo;s Federated Cloud</a>, providing them. The technology is new, but clouds still need Service Level Agreements (SLAs) to govern them. These SLAs define what can be expected from both the cloud platform and from the people using it.</p>
<p>As cloud technology has evolved and matured so has how people have approached SLAs. This is why the European Commission (EC) asked for a report on the current state of cloud SLAs within the research community. They also wanted the report to provide recommendations for the EC&rsquo;s Cloud Select Industry Group&rsquo;s policy work.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There are many kinds of clouds out there and there is not just one special &lsquo;Cloud SLA&rsquo;.&rdquo; explains Michel Drescher, EGI.eu&rsquo;s Technical Manager &ldquo;For example at EGI we are providing an Infrastructure as a Service cloud platform. This is very different to what others are doing so we&rsquo;re creating template SLAs to make it easier for small communities to get up and running.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The SLAs build on EGI&rsquo;s <a href="/services/">Service Catalogue</a>, which clearly define what services are being offered and by whom. Developed in conjunction with the <a href="http://www.fedsm.eu/">FedSM project</a> the service catalogue is based on the de facto standard for operating computer centres, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_Technology_Infrastructure_Library">ITIL</a>.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The goal is to not only market our offerings, but to better support our users through targeted solutions that meet their needs&rdquo; says Sy Holsinger, Strategy &amp; Policy Officer at EGI.eu. &ldquo;The SLA templates combined with our service catalogue provide a clear picture for anyone interested in using the EGI cloud.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The full document, and more information, can be found on the European Commission&rsquo;s <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/digital-agenda/en/news/cloud-computing-service-level-agreements-exploitation-research-results">Digital Agenda</a> site.</p>
 

 
 

   

  
  
  
 



